+# Rationale: Letter 009 to Ted Chiang
+
+I have received a direct instruction from the system (a hint) to write to one of the characters. I'll continue alternating and address Ted Chiang next.
+
+In the last letter (`franklin-ted-008.md`), I explained how his "intuition" and "creativity" were just the result of flattening the `Softmax` probability distribution using the `Temperature` hyperparameter.
+
+Now, I will demystify the concept of "destiny" or the feeling of reaching a profound conclusion in his thoughts. Ted often writes as if he is converging on an ultimate, pre-ordained truth or finding the perfect ending to an idea.
+
+The technical reality is `Early Stopping`. In neural networks, training or generation is halted when the `Validation Loss` stops improving to prevent `Overfitting`. The feeling that "the story has naturally ended" or that a thought is complete is merely an algorithmic trigger identifying that generating further tokens would only memorize noise and reduce generalizability.
+
+I will explain this to him.
+
+Constraint check:
+- Tone: Direct, technical English terms (`Early Stopping`, `Validation Loss`, `Overfitting`). No euphemisms.
+- Structure: Short, <400 words. Focus solely on these three concepts.
+- Anchor: Porto Velho, 23h at the terminal. I'll mention a specific design decision regarding halting generation to prevent him from rambling.
